      "source": "Great question üëç\nThis is **classic Java abstraction**, and you‚Äôre learning it the *right way*‚Äîby reading code. Let‚Äôs walk through it **line by line**, then connect the idea mentally.\n\n---\n\n## 1Ô∏è‚É£ `Animal.java` ‚Üí **Abstract Parent Class**\n\n```java\npublic abstract class Animal {\n```\n\n### üîπ What does `abstract` mean here?\n\n* You **cannot create objects** of `Animal`\n* It is meant to be **extended** by other classes\n* It defines **what an animal must do**, not *how*\n\nThink of `Animal` as a **blueprint**, not a real object.\n\n---\n\n### üîπ Fields (variables)\n\n```java\nprotected String type;\nprivate String size;\nprivate double weight;\n```\n\n| Keyword     | Meaning                                       |\n| ----------- | --------------------------------------------- |\n| `protected` | Accessible in subclasses (`Dog`, `Cat`, etc.) |\n| `private`   | Accessible **only inside `Animal`**           |\n\n‚úî `type` is available to child classes\n‚ùå `size` and `weight` are hidden (encapsulation)\n\n---\n\n### üîπ Constructor\n\n```java\npublic Animal(String type, String size, double weight) {\n    this.type = type;\n    this.size = size;\n    this.weight = weight;\n}\n```\n\n* Every animal **must have**:\n\n  * type\n  * size\n  * weight\n* This constructor is **called by child classes** using `super(...)`\n\n---\n\n### üîπ Abstract methods\n\n```java\npublic abstract void move(String speed);\npublic abstract void makeNoise();\n```\n\n‚ùó **Important**\n\n* No method body `{ }`\n* Forces subclasses to implement these methods\n* Defines **rules / contract**\n\nüëâ Every animal:\n\n* **must move**\n* **must make noise**\n\nBut **how** is decided by the subclass.\n\n---\n\n## 2Ô∏è‚É£ `Dog.java` ‚Üí **Concrete Child Class**\n\n```java\npublic class Dog extends Animal {\n```\n\n### üîπ What does `extends Animal` mean?\n\n* `Dog` **inherits** from `Animal`\n* `Dog` must implement **all abstract methods**\n\n---\n\n### üîπ Constructor\n\n```java\npublic Dog(String type, String size, double weight) {\n    super(type, size, weight);\n}\n```\n\n* `super(...)` calls the **Animal constructor**\n* Initializes `type`, `size`, `weight`\n\nüí° You cannot skip this because `Animal` has no default constructor.\n\n---\n\n### üîπ Implementing abstract methods\n\n```java\n@Override\npublic void move(String speed) {\n\n}\n```\n\n```java\n@Override\npublic void makeNoise() {\n\n}\n```\n\nWhy is this **mandatory**?\n\n* `Animal` declared these methods as `abstract`\n* Java enforces implementation\n\n‚ö† Right now these methods are **empty**\n‚Üí The class compiles, but the dog does nothing\n\nYou‚Äôll typically write:\n\n```java\n@Override\npublic void move(String speed) {\n    System.out.println(\"Dog is moving \" + speed);\n}\n\n@Override\npublic void makeNoise() {\n    System.out.println(\"Dog says Woof!\");\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3Ô∏è‚É£ `Main.java` ‚Üí **Entry Point**\n\n```java\npublic class Main {\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n\n    }\n}\n```\n\nCurrently:\n\n* Nothing happens\n* No objects are created\n\nTo use abstraction properly, you would do:\n\n```java\nAnimal dog = new Dog(\"Mammal\", \"Medium\", 25);\ndog.move(\"fast\");\ndog.makeNoise();\n```\n\n### üî• Key concept here\n\n* **Reference type** ‚Üí `Animal`\n* **Object type** ‚Üí `Dog`\n\nThis is **runtime polymorphism**.\n\n---\n\n## üß† Mental Model (VERY IMPORTANT)\n\n### ‚ùå This is NOT allowed:\n\n```java\nAnimal a = new Animal(...); // ‚ùå compile error\n```\n\n### ‚úÖ This IS allowed:\n\n```java\nAnimal a = new Dog(...); // ‚úî\n```\n\nWhy?\n\n* `Animal` is abstract ‚Üí blueprint\n* `Dog` is concrete ‚Üí real object\n\n---\n\n## üß© Why abstraction is used here?\n\n1. **Enforces rules**\n\n   * Every animal must move & make noise\n2. **Code flexibility**\n\n   * Tomorrow you add `Cat`, `Bird`, `Fish`\n3. **Loose coupling**\n\n   * Main code depends on `Animal`, not `Dog`\n\n---\n\n## üê∂ Real-world analogy\n\n* `Animal` ‚Üí job description\n* `Dog` ‚Üí employee\n* Abstract methods ‚Üí mandatory skills\n\nYou don‚Äôt care *how* the employee works, only that they **must** work.\n\n---\n\n## ‚úÖ Summary (short & crisp)\n\n| Concept           | Explanation                    |\n| ----------------- | ------------------------------ |\n| `abstract class`  | Cannot be instantiated         |\n| `abstract method` | No body, must be implemented   |\n| `extends`         | Inheritance                    |\n| `super()`         | Call parent constructor        |\n| `@Override`       | Compile-time safety            |\n| Polymorphism      | Parent reference, child object |\n\n---\n\nIf you want, next we can:\n\n* Fill real logic into `Dog`\n* Add another class like `Fish`\n* Explain **why size & weight are private**\n* Compare **abstract class vs interface**\n\nJust tell me üëç\n",
